<paragraph id="8B845534FFA6CC5D1A80FF439BCCFF14" blockId="5.[136,963,158,185]" box="[136,963,158,185]" pageId="5" pageNumber="261">
<heading id="D0CCE258FFA6CC5D1A80FF439BCCFF14" box="[136,963,158,185]" fontSize="11" level="2" pageId="5" pageNumber="261" reason="3">
<taxonomicName id="4C3B2EB7FFA6CC5D1A80FF439ADEFF15" authority="Van de Vijver &amp; E.Morales" authorityName="Van de Vijver &amp; E. Morales" authorityYear="2014" box="[136,721,158,185]" class="Bacillariophyceae" family="Fragilariaceae" genus="Staurosirella" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Chromista" order="Fragilariales" pageId="5" pageNumber="261" phylum="Bacillariophyta" rank="species" species="antarctica" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis id="B94F8926FFA6CC5D1A80FF439996FF15" bold="true" box="[136,409,158,185]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="261">Staurosirella antarctica</emphasis>
Van de Vijver &amp; E.Morales
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis id="B94F8926FFA6CC5D18D0FF429B22FF15" box="[728,813,159,184]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="261">
<taxonomicNameLabel id="A27C345DFFA6CC5D18D0FF429B22FF15" box="[728,813,159,184]" pageId="5" pageNumber="261" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation id="130049B1FFA6CC5D1933FF439BB3FF14" box="[827,956,158,185]" captionStart="FIGURES 26–51" captionStartId="4.[136,243,1735,1757]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,190,1711]" captionTargetId="figure-25@4.[151,1435,190,1711]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 26–51: Staurosirella antarctica Van de Vijver &amp; E.Morales sp. nov. All pictures taken from the holotype population (sample BY049). Figs 26–45. LM images. Fig. 45 shows a girdle view, whereas Figs 26–44 show valve views. Figs 46–51: SEM images. Fig. 46: Two entire frustules showing the linking spines, parts of the girdle bands and the mantle. Fig. 47: External view of an entire valve showing the heteropolar valve outline, the linking spines, the apical pore field and the striae. Fig. 48: Detail of the striae with slit-like areolae. Spines are positioned between the striae. Fig. 49: Detail of the apical pore field at the head pole showing 2 rows of small, rounded poroids separated from the striae. Fig. 50: Internal view of an entire valve. Fig. 51: External detail of the apical pore field at the foot pole. Scale bar represents 10 µm except for Figs 48, 49, 51 where scale bar = 1µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5138829" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5138829/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="261">Figs 26–51</figureCitation>
)
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B845534FFA6CC5D1A80FF379B8DFE19" blockId="5.[136,1452,234,436]" pageId="5" pageNumber="261">
Cells lanceolate to ovoid, heteropolar, with openly convex margins and subrostrate to rounded apices. Length 
<quantity id="4CC3F8D1FFA6CC5D1EA9FF379D11FF52" box="[1185,1310,234,256]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.25" metricValueMax="1.55" metricValueMin="0.95" pageId="5" pageNumber="261" unit="mm" value="12.5" valueMax="15.5" valueMin="9.5">9.5–15.5 µm</quantity>
, width 
<quantity id="4CC3F8D1FFA6CC5D1F6BFF3798EFFE8E" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.4" metricValueMax="3.9" metricValueMin="2.9" pageId="5" pageNumber="261" unit="mm" value="3.4" valueMax="3.9" valueMin="2.9">2.9–3.9 µm</quantity>
, stria density 
<quantity id="4CC3F8D1FFA6CC5D1B6AFED399A4FE89" box="[354,427,270,292]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.413" metricValueMax="2.54" metricValueMin="2.286" pageId="5" pageNumber="261" unit="in" value="9.5" valueMax="10.0" valueMin="9.0">9–10 in</quantity>
<quantity id="4CC3F8D1FFA6CC5D1BB8FED399FFFE8E" box="[432,496,270,291]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.0" pageId="5" pageNumber="261" unit="mm" value="10.0">10 µm</quantity>
. Central sternum narrow, linear to lanceolate, raised and forming a continuum with the virgae. Striae alternate, parallel in central area and radiate at apices. Areolae markedly lineolate, running continuously from valve face to mantle, 
<quantity id="4CC3F8D1FFA6CC5D1AB5FE8B991BFEC1" box="[189,276,342,364]" metricMagnitude="0" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.4605" metricValueMax="1.524" metricValueMin="1.3969999999999998" pageId="5" pageNumber="261" unit="in" value="57.5" valueMax="60.0" valueMin="55.0">55–60 in</quantity>
<quantity id="4CC3F8D1FFA6CC5D1B13FE8B9952FEC6" box="[283,349,342,363]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.0" pageId="5" pageNumber="261" unit="mm" value="10.0">10 µm</quantity>
, and bearing well-developed volae. Spines flat, spatulate and located on the virgae. One apical pore field at each apex, located on the valve mantle. Foot-pole apical pore field larger and compose of up to 5 rows of round poroids. Girdle bands open, non-perforated with valvocopula wider than rest of girdle elements.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C32106BFFFA6CC5D1A80FE3E9BFCFBB4" pageId="5" pageNumber="261" type="description">
<paragraph id="8B845534FFA6CC5D1A80FE3E9CCEFDC4" blockId="5.[136,1452,482,1445]" pageId="5" pageNumber="261">
<emphasis id="B94F8926FFA6CC5D1A80FE3E9940FE51" box="[136,335,482,509]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="261">
LM (
<figureCitation id="130049B1FFA6CC5D1AB6FE3E994EFE51" box="[190,321,482,509]" captionStart="FIGURES 26–51" captionStartId="4.[136,243,1735,1757]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,190,1711]" captionTargetId="figure-25@4.[151,1435,190,1711]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 26–51: Staurosirella antarctica Van de Vijver &amp; E.Morales sp. nov. All pictures taken from the holotype population (sample BY049). Figs 26–45. LM images. Fig. 45 shows a girdle view, whereas Figs 26–44 show valve views. Figs 46–51: SEM images. Fig. 46: Two entire frustules showing the linking spines, parts of the girdle bands and the mantle. Fig. 47: External view of an entire valve showing the heteropolar valve outline, the linking spines, the apical pore field and the striae. Fig. 48: Detail of the striae with slit-like areolae. Spines are positioned between the striae. Fig. 49: Detail of the apical pore field at the head pole showing 2 rows of small, rounded poroids separated from the striae. Fig. 50: Internal view of an entire valve. Fig. 51: External detail of the apical pore field at the foot pole. Scale bar represents 10 µm except for Figs 48, 49, 51 where scale bar = 1µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5138829" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5138829/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="261">Figs 26–45</figureCitation>
):
</emphasis>
Frustules are rectangular in girdle view (
<figureCitation id="130049B1FFA6CC5D1911FE3F9B63FE50" box="[793,876,482,509]" captionStart="FIGURES 26–51" captionStartId="4.[136,243,1735,1757]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,190,1711]" captionTargetId="figure-25@4.[151,1435,190,1711]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 26–51: Staurosirella antarctica Van de Vijver &amp; E.Morales sp. nov. All pictures taken from the holotype population (sample BY049). Figs 26–45. LM images. Fig. 45 shows a girdle view, whereas Figs 26–44 show valve views. Figs 46–51: SEM images. Fig. 46: Two entire frustules showing the linking spines, parts of the girdle bands and the mantle. Fig. 47: External view of an entire valve showing the heteropolar valve outline, the linking spines, the apical pore field and the striae. Fig. 48: Detail of the striae with slit-like areolae. Spines are positioned between the striae. Fig. 49: Detail of the apical pore field at the head pole showing 2 rows of small, rounded poroids separated from the striae. Fig. 50: Internal view of an entire valve. Fig. 51: External detail of the apical pore field at the foot pole. Scale bar represents 10 µm except for Figs 48, 49, 51 where scale bar = 1µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5138829" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5138829/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="261">Fig. 45</figureCitation>
). Valves are lanceolate to narrowly ovoid, faintly or conspicuously heteropolar with subrostrate to rounded apices (
<figureCitation id="130049B1FFA6CC5D1949FDDB9BCBFD8C" box="[833,964,518,545]" captionStart="FIGURES 26–51" captionStartId="4.[136,243,1735,1757]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,190,1711]" captionTargetId="figure-25@4.[151,1435,190,1711]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 26–51: Staurosirella antarctica Van de Vijver &amp; E.Morales sp. nov. All pictures taken from the holotype population (sample BY049). Figs 26–45. LM images. Fig. 45 shows a girdle view, whereas Figs 26–44 show valve views. Figs 46–51: SEM images. Fig. 46: Two entire frustules showing the linking spines, parts of the girdle bands and the mantle. Fig. 47: External view of an entire valve showing the heteropolar valve outline, the linking spines, the apical pore field and the striae. Fig. 48: Detail of the striae with slit-like areolae. Spines are positioned between the striae. Fig. 49: Detail of the apical pore field at the head pole showing 2 rows of small, rounded poroids separated from the striae. Fig. 50: Internal view of an entire valve. Fig. 51: External detail of the apical pore field at the foot pole. Scale bar represents 10 µm except for Figs 48, 49, 51 where scale bar = 1µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5138829" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5138829/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="261">Figs 26–44</figureCitation>
). Valve dimensions (n=25): length 
<quantity id="4CC3F8D1FFA6CC5D1F41FDDB98BFFDE8" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.25" metricValueMax="1.55" metricValueMin="0.95" pageId="5" pageNumber="261" unit="mm" value="12.5" valueMax="15.5" valueMin="9.5">9.5–15.5 µm</quantity>
, width 
<quantity id="4CC3F8D1FFA6CC5D1B0CFDF79987FDE8" box="[260,392,554,581]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.4" metricValueMax="3.9" metricValueMin="2.9" pageId="5" pageNumber="261" unit="mm" value="3.4" valueMax="3.9" valueMin="2.9">2.9–3.9 µm</quantity>
. The central sternum is narrow and linear to lanceolate. The striae are alternating, parallel and becoming slightly radiate near the apices, 
<quantity id="4CC3F8D1FFA6CC5D1868FD939ABAFDC5" box="[608,693,590,616]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.413" metricValueMax="2.54" metricValueMin="2.286" pageId="5" pageNumber="261" unit="in" value="9.5" valueMax="10.0" valueMin="9.0">9–10 in</quantity>
<quantity id="4CC3F8D1FFA6CC5D18B4FD939B07FDC4" box="[700,776,590,617]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.0" pageId="5" pageNumber="261" unit="mm" value="10.0">10 µm</quantity>
. The areolae are not discernible in LM.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B845534FFA6CC5D1AB5FDAE9BFCFBB4" blockId="5.[136,1452,482,1445]" pageId="5" pageNumber="261">
<emphasis id="B94F8926FFA6CC5D1AB5FDAE9996FD21" box="[189,409,626,653]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="261">
SEM (
<figureCitation id="130049B1FFA6CC5D1B0DFDAE9984FD21" box="[261,395,626,653]" captionStart="FIGURES 26–51" captionStartId="4.[136,243,1735,1757]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,190,1711]" captionTargetId="figure-25@4.[151,1435,190,1711]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 26–51: Staurosirella antarctica Van de Vijver &amp; E.Morales sp. nov. All pictures taken from the holotype population (sample BY049). Figs 26–45. LM images. Fig. 45 shows a girdle view, whereas Figs 26–44 show valve views. Figs 46–51: SEM images. Fig. 46: Two entire frustules showing the linking spines, parts of the girdle bands and the mantle. Fig. 47: External view of an entire valve showing the heteropolar valve outline, the linking spines, the apical pore field and the striae. Fig. 48: Detail of the striae with slit-like areolae. Spines are positioned between the striae. Fig. 49: Detail of the apical pore field at the head pole showing 2 rows of small, rounded poroids separated from the striae. Fig. 50: Internal view of an entire valve. Fig. 51: External detail of the apical pore field at the foot pole. Scale bar represents 10 µm except for Figs 48, 49, 51 where scale bar = 1µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5138829" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5138829/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="261">Figs 46–51</figureCitation>
):
</emphasis>
Frustules are linked by single, spatulate and solid linking spines, which are located on the costae at the valve face/mantle junction (
<figureCitation id="130049B1FFA6CC5D1850FD4B9AD1FD1C" box="[600,734,662,689]" captionStart="FIGURES 26–51" captionStartId="4.[136,243,1735,1757]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,190,1711]" captionTargetId="figure-25@4.[151,1435,190,1711]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 26–51: Staurosirella antarctica Van de Vijver &amp; E.Morales sp. nov. All pictures taken from the holotype population (sample BY049). Figs 26–45. LM images. Fig. 45 shows a girdle view, whereas Figs 26–44 show valve views. Figs 46–51: SEM images. Fig. 46: Two entire frustules showing the linking spines, parts of the girdle bands and the mantle. Fig. 47: External view of an entire valve showing the heteropolar valve outline, the linking spines, the apical pore field and the striae. Fig. 48: Detail of the striae with slit-like areolae. Spines are positioned between the striae. Fig. 49: Detail of the apical pore field at the head pole showing 2 rows of small, rounded poroids separated from the striae. Fig. 50: Internal view of an entire valve. Fig. 51: External detail of the apical pore field at the foot pole. Scale bar represents 10 µm except for Figs 48, 49, 51 where scale bar = 1µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5138829" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5138829/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="261">Figs 46–49</figureCitation>
). The valve surface is slightly undulate due to the raised costae and the axial area, which are smooth (
<figureCitation id="130049B1FFA6CC5D1836FD679A9BFD79" box="[574,660,698,724]" captionStart="FIGURES 26–51" captionStartId="4.[136,243,1735,1757]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,190,1711]" captionTargetId="figure-25@4.[151,1435,190,1711]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 26–51: Staurosirella antarctica Van de Vijver &amp; E.Morales sp. nov. All pictures taken from the holotype population (sample BY049). Figs 26–45. LM images. Fig. 45 shows a girdle view, whereas Figs 26–44 show valve views. Figs 46–51: SEM images. Fig. 46: Two entire frustules showing the linking spines, parts of the girdle bands and the mantle. Fig. 47: External view of an entire valve showing the heteropolar valve outline, the linking spines, the apical pore field and the striae. Fig. 48: Detail of the striae with slit-like areolae. Spines are positioned between the striae. Fig. 49: Detail of the apical pore field at the head pole showing 2 rows of small, rounded poroids separated from the striae. Fig. 50: Internal view of an entire valve. Fig. 51: External detail of the apical pore field at the foot pole. Scale bar represents 10 µm except for Figs 48, 49, 51 where scale bar = 1µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5138829" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5138829/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="261">Fig. 47</figureCitation>
). Apical pore fields are present on each apex, better developed at the foot-pole that at the head-pole. They are located on the valve mantle and composed of several, usually up to 6, rows of small round poroids (
<figureCitation id="130049B1FFA6CC5D1B71FCDF9A28FCB0" box="[377,551,770,797]" captionStart="FIGURES 26–51" captionStartId="4.[136,243,1735,1757]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,190,1711]" captionTargetId="figure-25@4.[151,1435,190,1711]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 26–51: Staurosirella antarctica Van de Vijver &amp; E.Morales sp. nov. All pictures taken from the holotype population (sample BY049). Figs 26–45. LM images. Fig. 45 shows a girdle view, whereas Figs 26–44 show valve views. Figs 46–51: SEM images. Fig. 46: Two entire frustules showing the linking spines, parts of the girdle bands and the mantle. Fig. 47: External view of an entire valve showing the heteropolar valve outline, the linking spines, the apical pore field and the striae. Fig. 48: Detail of the striae with slit-like areolae. Spines are positioned between the striae. Fig. 49: Detail of the apical pore field at the head pole showing 2 rows of small, rounded poroids separated from the striae. Fig. 50: Internal view of an entire valve. Fig. 51: External detail of the apical pore field at the foot pole. Scale bar represents 10 µm except for Figs 48, 49, 51 where scale bar = 1µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5138829" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5138829/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="261">Figs 47, 49, 51</figureCitation>
). Internally, the apical pore fields are well separated from the striae and formed within a depression at the valve apices (
<figureCitation id="130049B1FFA6CC5D184DFCFB9A96FCEC" box="[581,665,806,833]" captionStart="FIGURES 26–51" captionStartId="4.[136,243,1735,1757]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,190,1711]" captionTargetId="figure-25@4.[151,1435,190,1711]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 26–51: Staurosirella antarctica Van de Vijver &amp; E.Morales sp. nov. All pictures taken from the holotype population (sample BY049). Figs 26–45. LM images. Fig. 45 shows a girdle view, whereas Figs 26–44 show valve views. Figs 46–51: SEM images. Fig. 46: Two entire frustules showing the linking spines, parts of the girdle bands and the mantle. Fig. 47: External view of an entire valve showing the heteropolar valve outline, the linking spines, the apical pore field and the striae. Fig. 48: Detail of the striae with slit-like areolae. Spines are positioned between the striae. Fig. 49: Detail of the apical pore field at the head pole showing 2 rows of small, rounded poroids separated from the striae. Fig. 50: Internal view of an entire valve. Fig. 51: External detail of the apical pore field at the foot pole. Scale bar represents 10 µm except for Figs 48, 49, 51 where scale bar = 1µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5138829" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5138829/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="261">Fig. 50</figureCitation>
). Rimoportulae are absent. The striae are composed of narrow slit-like to rectangular areolae running continuously from the valve face onto the mantle and becoming smaller toward the axial and mantle abvalvar areas (
<figureCitation id="130049B1FFA6CC5D1BBFFCB39A37FC25" box="[439,568,878,904]" captionStart="FIGURES 26–51" captionStartId="4.[136,243,1735,1757]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,190,1711]" captionTargetId="figure-25@4.[151,1435,190,1711]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 26–51: Staurosirella antarctica Van de Vijver &amp; E.Morales sp. nov. All pictures taken from the holotype population (sample BY049). Figs 26–45. LM images. Fig. 45 shows a girdle view, whereas Figs 26–44 show valve views. Figs 46–51: SEM images. Fig. 46: Two entire frustules showing the linking spines, parts of the girdle bands and the mantle. Fig. 47: External view of an entire valve showing the heteropolar valve outline, the linking spines, the apical pore field and the striae. Fig. 48: Detail of the striae with slit-like areolae. Spines are positioned between the striae. Fig. 49: Detail of the apical pore field at the head pole showing 2 rows of small, rounded poroids separated from the striae. Fig. 50: Internal view of an entire valve. Fig. 51: External detail of the apical pore field at the foot pole. Scale bar represents 10 µm except for Figs 48, 49, 51 where scale bar = 1µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5138829" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5138829/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="261">Figs 48, 49</figureCitation>
). Areolae ca. 
<quantity id="4CC3F8D1FFA6CC5D18C6FCB39B3FFC25" box="[718,816,878,905]" metricMagnitude="0" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.4605" metricValueMax="1.524" metricValueMin="1.3969999999999998" pageId="5" pageNumber="261" unit="in" value="57.5" valueMax="60.0" valueMin="55.0">55–60 in</quantity>
<quantity id="4CC3F8D1FFA6CC5D193EFCB39B71FC24" box="[822,894,878,905]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.0" pageId="5" pageNumber="261" unit="mm" value="10.0">10 µm</quantity>
along the striae (
<figureCitation id="130049B1FFA6CC5D1E34FCB39CB0FC25" box="[1084,1215,878,904]" captionStart="FIGURES 26–51" captionStartId="4.[136,243,1735,1757]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,190,1711]" captionTargetId="figure-25@4.[151,1435,190,1711]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 26–51: Staurosirella antarctica Van de Vijver &amp; E.Morales sp. nov. All pictures taken from the holotype population (sample BY049). Figs 26–45. LM images. Fig. 45 shows a girdle view, whereas Figs 26–44 show valve views. Figs 46–51: SEM images. Fig. 46: Two entire frustules showing the linking spines, parts of the girdle bands and the mantle. Fig. 47: External view of an entire valve showing the heteropolar valve outline, the linking spines, the apical pore field and the striae. Fig. 48: Detail of the striae with slit-like areolae. Spines are positioned between the striae. Fig. 49: Detail of the apical pore field at the head pole showing 2 rows of small, rounded poroids separated from the striae. Fig. 50: Internal view of an entire valve. Fig. 51: External detail of the apical pore field at the foot pole. Scale bar represents 10 µm except for Figs 48, 49, 51 where scale bar = 1µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5138829" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5138829/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="261">Figs 47–49</figureCitation>
). The mantle areolae, usually 4-5, are gradually becoming smaller than the areolae toward the axial area (
<figureCitation id="130049B1FFA6CC5D1E45FC4F9CACFC01" box="[1101,1187,914,940]" captionStart="FIGURES 26–51" captionStartId="4.[136,243,1735,1757]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,190,1711]" captionTargetId="figure-25@4.[151,1435,190,1711]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 26–51: Staurosirella antarctica Van de Vijver &amp; E.Morales sp. nov. All pictures taken from the holotype population (sample BY049). Figs 26–45. LM images. Fig. 45 shows a girdle view, whereas Figs 26–44 show valve views. Figs 46–51: SEM images. Fig. 46: Two entire frustules showing the linking spines, parts of the girdle bands and the mantle. Fig. 47: External view of an entire valve showing the heteropolar valve outline, the linking spines, the apical pore field and the striae. Fig. 48: Detail of the striae with slit-like areolae. Spines are positioned between the striae. Fig. 49: Detail of the apical pore field at the head pole showing 2 rows of small, rounded poroids separated from the striae. Fig. 50: Internal view of an entire valve. Fig. 51: External detail of the apical pore field at the foot pole. Scale bar represents 10 µm except for Figs 48, 49, 51 where scale bar = 1µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5138829" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5138829/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="261">Fig. 48</figureCitation>
). The volae are clearly developed and form a complex structure within the areolae (
<figureCitation id="130049B1FFA6CC5D194CFC6B9BC9FC7D" box="[836,966,950,976]" captionStart="FIGURES 26–51" captionStartId="4.[136,243,1735,1757]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,190,1711]" captionTargetId="figure-25@4.[151,1435,190,1711]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 26–51: Staurosirella antarctica Van de Vijver &amp; E.Morales sp. nov. All pictures taken from the holotype population (sample BY049). Figs 26–45. LM images. Fig. 45 shows a girdle view, whereas Figs 26–44 show valve views. Figs 46–51: SEM images. Fig. 46: Two entire frustules showing the linking spines, parts of the girdle bands and the mantle. Fig. 47: External view of an entire valve showing the heteropolar valve outline, the linking spines, the apical pore field and the striae. Fig. 48: Detail of the striae with slit-like areolae. Spines are positioned between the striae. Fig. 49: Detail of the apical pore field at the head pole showing 2 rows of small, rounded poroids separated from the striae. Fig. 50: Internal view of an entire valve. Fig. 51: External detail of the apical pore field at the foot pole. Scale bar represents 10 µm except for Figs 48, 49, 51 where scale bar = 1µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5138829" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5138829/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="261">Fig. 47–49</figureCitation>
). Internally, the costae are also raised and thickened compared to the striae (
<figureCitation id="130049B1FFA6CC5D1809FC079A5AFC58" box="[513,597,986,1013]" captionStart="FIGURES 26–51" captionStartId="4.[136,243,1735,1757]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,190,1711]" captionTargetId="figure-25@4.[151,1435,190,1711]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 26–51: Staurosirella antarctica Van de Vijver &amp; E.Morales sp. nov. All pictures taken from the holotype population (sample BY049). Figs 26–45. LM images. Fig. 45 shows a girdle view, whereas Figs 26–44 show valve views. Figs 46–51: SEM images. Fig. 46: Two entire frustules showing the linking spines, parts of the girdle bands and the mantle. Fig. 47: External view of an entire valve showing the heteropolar valve outline, the linking spines, the apical pore field and the striae. Fig. 48: Detail of the striae with slit-like areolae. Spines are positioned between the striae. Fig. 49: Detail of the apical pore field at the head pole showing 2 rows of small, rounded poroids separated from the striae. Fig. 50: Internal view of an entire valve. Fig. 51: External detail of the apical pore field at the foot pole. Scale bar represents 10 µm except for Figs 48, 49, 51 where scale bar = 1µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5138829" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5138829/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="261">Fig. 50</figureCitation>
). The girdle bands are open and lack perforations (
<figureCitation id="130049B1FFA6CC5D1E82FC079CD1FC58" box="[1162,1246,986,1013]" captionStart="FIGURES 26–51" captionStartId="4.[136,243,1735,1757]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,190,1711]" captionTargetId="figure-25@4.[151,1435,190,1711]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 26–51: Staurosirella antarctica Van de Vijver &amp; E.Morales sp. nov. All pictures taken from the holotype population (sample BY049). Figs 26–45. LM images. Fig. 45 shows a girdle view, whereas Figs 26–44 show valve views. Figs 46–51: SEM images. Fig. 46: Two entire frustules showing the linking spines, parts of the girdle bands and the mantle. Fig. 47: External view of an entire valve showing the heteropolar valve outline, the linking spines, the apical pore field and the striae. Fig. 48: Detail of the striae with slit-like areolae. Spines are positioned between the striae. Fig. 49: Detail of the apical pore field at the head pole showing 2 rows of small, rounded poroids separated from the striae. Fig. 50: Internal view of an entire valve. Fig. 51: External detail of the apical pore field at the foot pole. Scale bar represents 10 µm except for Figs 48, 49, 51 where scale bar = 1µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5138829" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5138829/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="261">Fig. 46</figureCitation>
). The valvocopula are presumably fimbriate and wider than the other narrower copulae (
<figureCitation id="130049B1FFA6CC5D199AFC239BE8FBB4" box="[914,999,1022,1049]" captionStart="FIGURES 26–51" captionStartId="4.[136,243,1735,1757]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,190,1711]" captionTargetId="figure-25@4.[151,1435,190,1711]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 26–51: Staurosirella antarctica Van de Vijver &amp; E.Morales sp. nov. All pictures taken from the holotype population (sample BY049). Figs 26–45. LM images. Fig. 45 shows a girdle view, whereas Figs 26–44 show valve views. Figs 46–51: SEM images. Fig. 46: Two entire frustules showing the linking spines, parts of the girdle bands and the mantle. Fig. 47: External view of an entire valve showing the heteropolar valve outline, the linking spines, the apical pore field and the striae. Fig. 48: Detail of the striae with slit-like areolae. Spines are positioned between the striae. Fig. 49: Detail of the apical pore field at the head pole showing 2 rows of small, rounded poroids separated from the striae. Fig. 50: Internal view of an entire valve. Fig. 51: External detail of the apical pore field at the foot pole. Scale bar represents 10 µm except for Figs 48, 49, 51 where scale bar = 1µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5138829" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5138829/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="261">Fig. 46</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
