<subSubSection id="C32106BFFFA6CC5D1AB5FB6F99EAFA09" pageId="5" pageNumber="261" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph id="8B845534FFA6CC5D1AB5FB6F99EAFA09" blockId="5.[136,1452,482,1445]" pageId="5" pageNumber="261">
<emphasis id="B94F8926FFA6CC5D1AB5FB6F99D8FB61" bold="true" box="[189,471,1202,1228]" pageId="5" pageNumber="261">Ecology &amp; Distribution</emphasis>
:—Due to force-fitting, all 
<taxonomicName id="4C3B2EB7FFA6CC5D1905FB6F9B92FB61" box="[781,925,1202,1228]" class="Bacillariophyceae" family="Fragilariaceae" genus="Staurosirella" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Chromista" order="Fragilariales" pageId="5" pageNumber="261" phylum="Bacillariophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B94F8926FFA6CC5D1905FB6F9B92FB61" box="[781,925,1202,1228]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="261">Staurosirella</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
populations in the Maritime Antarctic Region have been grouped under 
<taxonomicName id="4C3B2EB7FFA6CC5D1BBAFB0B9B3BFB5D" authorityName="D. M. Williams &amp; Round" authorityYear="1987" baseAuthorityName="Ehrenb." baseAuthorityYear="1843" box="[434,820,1238,1265]" class="Bacillariophyceae" family="Fragilariaceae" genus="Staurosirella" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Chromista" order="Fragilariales" pageId="5" pageNumber="261" phylum="Bacillariophyta" rank="species" species="pinnata" subGenus="Fragilaria">
<emphasis id="B94F8926FFA6CC5D1BBAFB0B9A4DFB5D" box="[434,578,1238,1264]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="261">Staurosirella</emphasis>
(
<emphasis id="B94F8926FFA6CC5D185DFB0B9AC4FB5D" box="[597,715,1238,1264]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="261">Fragilaria</emphasis>
) 
<emphasis id="B94F8926FFA6CC5D18D6FB0A9B3BFB5D" box="[734,820,1239,1264]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="261">pinnata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
making it at present impossible to determine the exact distribution of the new species. 
<taxonomicName id="4C3B2EB7FFA6CC5D1BFAFB279AF2FAB9" authorityName="Van de Vijver &amp; E. Morales" authorityYear="2014" box="[498,765,1274,1300]" class="Bacillariophyceae" family="Fragilariaceae" genus="Staurosirella" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Chromista" order="Fragilariales" pageId="5" pageNumber="261" phylum="Bacillariophyta" rank="species" species="antarctica">
<emphasis id="B94F8926FFA6CC5D1BFAFB279AF2FAB9" box="[498,765,1274,1300]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="261">Staurosirella antarctica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was with certainty found in one small pool (
<quantity id="4CC3F8D1FFA6CC5D1EF5FB279D37FAB8" box="[1277,1336,1274,1301]" metricMagnitude="1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.0" pageId="5" pageNumber="261" unit="m" value="10.0">10 m</quantity>
diameter) close to Limnopolar Lake. On one side of the pool water was dripping from a rock surface in the pool while on the other side, water was flowing out in a small braided river. The bottom was covered sediment with fine sediment and larger pebbles. Thin algal mats were present in the pool. The pool had a rather alkaline pH (7.6) with a low specific conductance value (58 µS/cm).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
